I'm reading Thicker than Blood, I think that there's potential here but a lot of stuff is a little too heavy handed. The dialogue doesn't feel natural, and I'd recommend reading it out loud a couple times to make sure your characters are saying. The stuttering pisses me off because it's excessive, and actively works to the detriment of immersion. I kept thinking of this scene while reading through. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IAJTllCrvn0
I can relate to Vin's conflict because I've felt that kind of regret from sleeping with someone. In my case it was more that I was so focused on the act that I didn't give a shit about the person, and I felt disgusted with myself when everything was over.
The problem I have is that you didn't make the plot or the characters are interesting enough to really hold on to my attention. I don't really know how you would fix that, especially for a low key story like this, but again, I think that some more attention to the dialogue would help.

Anonymous Wed 31 Mar 2021 00:22:07 No.37527776 Report
Quoted By: >>37528302
>>37527038
The scene from Goodfellas is an exaggeration of what's going on. In that scene Joe Pesci's character is mocking Michael Imperioli's character because the latter is unable to form a sentence without fumbling over his own words, partially because of his nerves. I was bringing attention to the fact that it's used excessively.
I do believe all the problems are related. I think that there needs to be more dialogue, and that it needs to go through more passes before publishing.
Chapter 4 has a few good scenes, establishing some level of comfort between the leads. Shit like Vin interrupting the movie to ask a stupid question may seem like throwaway dialogue, but you'd be surprised how important those sorts of interactions are for characterization. There isn't enough like that in the work as it stands.
Improving the quality of the dialogue is a different fix, keep in mind that I consider body language to be an important element of that. There's a lot of focus on the eyes, but not as much with the mouth or hands. Another thing is the pet name. When she's dropping 'cutie' like two or three times in a row, it comes off as forced and not endearing. It would be like your mother using your name 3 times in a row when she's nagging you about going to your cousin's wedding. And there's little things like that all over. Just ask yourself when you're passing through the dialogue, "Would a real person say this, especially in this way?"
